The first panning shots were filmed in 1893; the first animation appeared in 1899; and the first close up scenes in films were made in 1900. Films then were often called "chase films". Special lighting effects such as dimming to create suspense and putting hand-painted glass in front of the projector developed shortly. Actors and Actresses first received payment in 1903. Movie making with axial rotation and other technology developed afterwards. The market of early film industry was mainly for Americans and Europeans except for French. The first film with sound was "The Jazz Singermade in 1927. "Silent" films, however, do had live band or orchestra accompaniments and live narration to make sounds in the film viewing experience. Early silent films may also have intermissions with text projected on the screen to clarify the plot or lines said by characters.
